"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46152","Department for Transport","false","2014-04-03","<p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is a matter for the Train Operator to ensure that the appropriate standards of cleanliness are met on trains.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>More information can be obtained from the Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC) which can be contacted at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2nd Floor</p><p> </p><p>200 Aldersgate Street</p><p> </p><p>London<br> EC1A 4HD</p><p> </p><p>Tel: 020 7841 8000</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46152/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46152/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, who is responsible for enforcing standards in the hygiene of toilets on trains; and who is accountable for any failings in this area.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","194496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46153","Department for Transport","false","2014-04-03","<p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The following subsidiary companies owned by Directly Operated Railways have been used in connection with the Direct Awards programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>· West Coast Main Line Company Limited</p><p> </p><p>· Northern Trains Limited</p><p> </p><p>· GW Railway Limited</p><p> </p><p>· South Eastern Trains Limited</p><p> </p><p>· Thameslink Limited</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All of these companies are currently dormant.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The company also owns the East Coast Main Line Company Ltd which operates rail services on the East Coast Main Line and the following companies, both of which are dormant.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>· OQS Rail Limited</p><p> </p><p>· Hay's Rail limited</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46153/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46153/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what subsidiary companies of Directly Operated Railways have been created in connection with the direct awards programme.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","194503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46154","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-03","<p /> <p /> <p>The procurement exercise is still in progress. As a consequence, at this stage the information requested is not yet available and therefore cannot be disclosed.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46154/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46154/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which companies have entered into contracts to deliver community work placements in each region and country of the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","194506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46155","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-03","<p>We have been allocated up to £60M in 2007-2013 ESF programme funding to help support people back into employment through community work placements.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46155/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46155/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what funding the European Social Fund will contribute to community work placement contracts in England for 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","194507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46156","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-07","<p /> <p /> <p>The deployment of staff and efficient use of the departmental estate is always subject to review. At the present time, there are no plans to relocate Departmental staff to the South West in the next five years.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46156/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46156/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many posts in his Department will be relocated to the South West in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","194568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46157","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-03","<p /> <p /> <p>I refer the hon. Member to the written ministerial statement I made on 27 March 2014. Official Report col. 56-57WS.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm140327/wmstext/140327m0002.htm#14032769000011" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm140327/wmstext/140327m0002.htm#14032769000011</a></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46157/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46157/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2013, Official Report, column 419W, on employment and support allowance, whether his Department expects to complete the incapacity benefit reassessment process in April 2014.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","194546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46158","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-07","<p /> <p /> <p>The permitted work rules in Employment and Support Allowance are based on those which applied to Incapacity Benefit. This approach was supported by evidence contained in DWP Research Report 268 “Final outcome from Permitted Work Rules”.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46158/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46158/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his letter of 20 March 2014, what the evidential basis is for his statement that allowing people receiving employment and support allowance to do some work within a specified 52 week period is the best way of encouraging a move towards work of 16 hours or more a week.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","194563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46246","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-03","<p>Over 600,000 homes have received energy efficiency improvements so far as a result of the Coalition's Energy Company Obligation and Green Deal initiatives. Green Deal assessments are stimulating interest and there had been over 160,000 by the end of February. Yesterday we announced additional £88 million from the Government to drive street by street roll out under the Green Deal Communities scheme.</p><p> </p><p>We expect the Green Deal market to continue to expand in 2014 and beyond.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46246/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/46246/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-31","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps he is taking to help households improve their energy efficiency.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","903482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45785","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-04-07","<p>The Government's International Education Strategy, published in July 2013, included an analysis of the value of international education to the UK. This analysis showed that international students across all parts of the education sector (higher education, further education, English language training, and independent schools) were estimated to contribute £13.6bn to the UK economy in 2011. More recent data indicates that this figure rose to £13.9bn in 2012.</p><p> </p><p>International students also bring indirect economic benefits to the UK, including: strengthening the quality, diversity and reputation of the UK education sector; providing a pipeline of prospective students who may study at higher levels in the UK; and improving overseas business, research, social and cultural links.</p><p> </p><p>The International Education Strategy and the accompanying analytical narrative can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-education-strategy-global-growth-and-prosperity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/international-education-strategy-global-growth-and-prosperity</a>.</p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45785/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45785/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the economic benefits to the UK of international students.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","194285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45786","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-04-07","<p>The Home Office published an impact assessment on its website on the 11 October 2013 entitled ‘Regulating migrant access to health services in the UK', in which it estimates the impact of implementing a health surcharge as outlined in the Immigration Bill. The Home Office predicts that implementing a health surcharge could cause Tier 4 visa grants to fall by approximately 830, which will have an impact on higher education providers of approximately £11 million per year. The surcharge is £200 per annum for most migrants however, to reflect their contribution to UK growth, a concession was factored into the Immigration Bill for students - they will pay £150 per annum rather than the full cost.</p><p> </p><p>BIS will continue to work closely with the Home Office and the higher education sector to monitor the effects of the surcharge on student numbers and to ensure that the impact is manageable.</p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45786/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45786/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the effect on higher education providers of charging fees to international students for use of the NHS.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","194286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45787","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-04-07","<p>The Government welcomes the benefits that international students bring to the UK as highlighted in theOxford Economics report entitled Economic Costs and Benefits of International Students, January 2013.</p><p> </p><p>In July the same year, we published our International Education Strategy which estimated that in 2011/12 international higher education students contributed £10.2bn to the UK economy through tuition fees and living expenses. The Strategy also recognised the wider benefits that students bring in boosting the local economy where they study, as well as enhancing our cultural life, and broadening the educational experience of the UK students they study alongside. It is because we value this contribution that there is no cap on the number of genuine overseas students who can come to the UK, nor do we have plans to introduce one.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>After completion of study, all students who can secure a skilled job from a licensed sponsor and are paid at least £20,300 are welcome to stay and work in the UK. Those who complete a PhD have up to a year to find a graduate level job and move on to Tier 2 or move on to the graduate entrepreneur or exceptional talent schemes in Tier 1.</p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45787/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45787/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the findings of the Oxford Economics report commissioned by the University of Sheffield entitled the Economic Costs and Benefits of International Students, January 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","194284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45790","HM Treasury","false","2014-05-07","<p>The Major Infrastructure Tracking Unit is part of Infrastructure UK, a team of 70 FTE staff.</p>","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Danny Alexander",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45790/answer","Biography information for Danny Alexander","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45790/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many full-time equivalent staff work in his Department's Major Infrastructure Tracking Unit.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","194287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45793","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-02","<p /> <p /> <p>The information is not readily available and has not previously been published as official statistics.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45793/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45793/answer","Wirral West","Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45793/answer/previousversion/4302","Biography information for Esther McVey","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many social housing tenants who were liable to pay the under-occupancy penalty have moved house since 1 April 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","194296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45794","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-02","<p /> <p /> <p>We have already commissioned a two year evaluation of the effects of the removal of the spare room subsidy across Great Britain. The evaluation commenced in April 2013 and is being led by Ipsos-MORI and includes the Cambridge Centre for Housing and Planning Research. The final report will be published in late 2015.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45794/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45794/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer to the hon. Member for Rhondda of 27 March 2014, Official Report, column 347W, on housing benefit: social rented sector, if he will commission a one year evaluation of the effects of the under-occupancy penalty.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","194295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45795","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-04-02","<p> </p><p> </p><p>It is still too early in the policy's lifetime to draw any firm conclusions as to its effect, including the number of tenants who have moved home. Rent arrears can have multiple causes and levels tend to fluctuate over time. A longer timeframe than one year is required in order to see whether and, if so, to what extent the removal of the spare room subsidy has impacted on rent arrears levels.</p><p>A consortium led by Ipsos-MORI and which includes the Cambridge Centre for Housing and Planning Research has been commissioned to carry out a two year monitoring of the effects of the removal of the spare room subsidy measure across Great Britain.</p><p>The Homes and Communities Agency reported in February that the median level of arrears among the larger housing associations had fallen from 4.1% in the second quarter of 2013-14 to 3.9% in the third quarter of 2013-14.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45795/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45795/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons his Department has not published data on the effects of the under-occupancy penalty on the number of social housing tenants who have moved home or fallen into rent arrears.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","194297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45798","Department for Education","false","2014-04-02","<p>I refer the Rt. Hon. Lady to the Answer I gave on 1 April 2014, Official Report, col. 631W, on Schools: Musical Instruments.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45798/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45798/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of secondary school children in England learning to play a musical instrument in school (a) paid a charge and (b) received their tuition free of charge in school years (i) 2009-10, (ii) 2010-11, (iii) 2011-12, (iv) 2012-13 and (v) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","194313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45800","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-02","<p>National Grid, as delivery body for Electricity Market Reform, will run the first capacity auction in December 2014, subject to the passage of secondary legislation and state aid approval being received. Pre-qualification for the first capacity auction is expected to open on 4 August 2014 and the first round of the auction is expected to take place on 9 December 2014. Consequently, National Grid has not yet received any applications for agreements under the Capacity Market.</p><p> </p><p>A detailed timetable for the implementation of the Capacity Market is available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/268629/Capacity_Market_Implementation_Plan_FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/268629/Capacity_Market_Implementation_Plan_FINAL.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45800/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45800/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many applications his Department has received for (a) one-year, (b) three-year and (c) 15-year contracts relating to (i) gas and (ii) coal under the capacity market.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","194282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45801","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-03","<p>I would like to apologise on behalf of the Department of Energy and Climate Change for the delay in replying to the Hon Member for Sunderland Central. My hon. Friend the Minister of State for Energy has since responded to this letter on 1 April 2014.</p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45801/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45801/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when he will reply to the letter from the hon. Member for Sunderland Central dated 27 February 2014 relating to the Eggborough power station.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","194302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45802","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-07","<p>NMP is the parent body organisation for Sellafield Ltd, the site licence company that operates Sellafield site under contract to the NDA. NMP, Sellafield Ltd and the NDA work collaboratively to support the socio-economic agenda in West Cumbria, with all three organisations having focussed their activities through Britain's Energy Coast, the private/public sector partnership established to promote and develop the economic prospects of the area. DECC has no direct role in assessing NMP's performance in this area which is a matter for the NDA.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45802/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45802/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment his Department has made of the socio-economic development performance of NMP in West Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","194320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45803","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-07","<p>Magnox Ltd is the site licence company that operates 10 Magnox sites under contract to the NDA. Magnox Ltd published a socio-economic strategy for its sites in 2011, which includes Hunterston A in North Ayrshire. DECC has no direct role in assessing Magnox's performance in this area which is a matter for the NDA.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45803/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45803/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment his Department has made of the socio-economic development performance of Magnox in North Ayrshire.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","194319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45804","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-02","<p>Government's plans for the Capacity Market and interim arrangements being put in place by National Grid ahead of this will offer an opportunity to extend the life of existing capacity where it is economically efficient to do so. Subject to state aid approval the first Capacity Market auction will take place in late 2014 for delivery in winter 2018. This will ensure sufficient capacity into the coming decades by offering regular payments to existing and new generation capacity that is successful at auction.</p><p> </p><p>In advance of this National Grid has developed Supplemental Balancing Reserve, a new balancing service through which it will be able to procure further capacity should it be needed, including capacity that is or otherwise intends to mothball or close. National Grid will only seek to competitively procure the amount of capacity that its forecast determines necessary and expect to run an initial tender process this spring for capacity for the winter of 2014/15 and 2015/16, with the possibility of extending this period if necessary.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45804/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45804/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether his Department has plans to extend the life of generating capacity currently scheduled to be closed in the event that delays in new investment arise as a result of uncertainty about the outcome of the competition investigation by the Competition and Markets Authority.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","194312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45805","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-07","<p> </p><p>There is no specific published data on the amount of wheat grown in the UK that is used for bioethanol. However it is possible to provide an estimate. Defra's statistics on ‘The Area of Crops Grown For Bioenergy in England and the UK: 2008 – 2012' published in December 2013 include data reported under the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) on the volume of bioethanol supplied to the UK road transport market with information on the feedstock and the country of origin of the feedstock. By applying appropriate conversion factors, it is possible to derive an estimate of the equivalent tonnage and crop area of wheat grown and used to produce bioethanol. These figures are outlined in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/289168/nonfood-statsnotice2012-12mar14.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/289168/nonfood-statsnotice2012-12mar14.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>UK wheat areas used to produce bioethanol supplied to the UK road transport market 2008/9 - 2012/13 </strong><strong>Wheat (RTFO Year: 15 April n-1 to 14 April n) </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Volume of bioethanol (million litres)</strong><strong>(b) </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Tonnage of crop implied ('000 tonnes)</strong><strong>(c) </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>wheat yield (t/ha)</strong><strong>(d)(e) </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Area implied (thousand ha) and % of UK total wheat area</strong><strong>(e) </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 1: 15 April 2008 - 14 April 2009</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>8.3</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 2: 15 April 2009 - 14 April 2010</p></td><td><p>0.9</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>7.9</p></td><td><p>0.3 (0%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 3: 15 April 2010 - 14 April 2011(a)</p></td><td><p>211.9</p></td><td><p>581</p></td><td><p>7.7</p></td><td><p>75.4 (4%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 4: 15 April 2011 - 14 April 2012</p></td><td><p>17.9</p></td><td><p>49</p></td><td><p>7.7</p></td><td><p>6.3 (0%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 5: 15 April 2012 - 14 April 2013 (provisional)(f)</p></td><td><p>48.2</p></td><td><p>132</p></td><td><p>6.7</p></td><td><p>19.6 (1%)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>(a) This includes an estimated 92 million tonnes of bioethanol produced from wheat used for markets other than for UK Road Transport.</p><p> </p><p>(b) All wheat volumes above were grown on previously cropped land.</p><p> </p><p>(c) Conversion: 365 litres bioethanol = 1 tonne wheat grain (at 15% moisture). Source: Department for Transport commissioned research.</p><p> </p><p>(d) Source: Defra annual Cereal and Oilseed Rape Production Survey (In 2012 the Cereal Production Survey and Oilseed Rape Production Survey were brought together to reduce costs Cereal Production Survey) UK yield at year n-1. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-of-the-agricultural-industry" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-of-the-agricultural-industry</a></p><p> </p><p>(e) Source: Defra June Survey of Agriculture. UK area at year n-1. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-of-the-agricultural-industry" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-of-the-agricultural-industry</a></p><p> </p><p>(e) Figures for 2012-13 (Year 5) are as of 15 September 2013 and are not final.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The RTFO data exclude UK biofuel production from UK grown wheat which may be subsequently exported, although the 2010/11 figure also includes an estimate of bioethanol produced from wheat and used for other markets or exported. Similarly, data is not available on wheat grown in the UK which is exported for possible biofuel production outside the UK.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-04-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45805/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45805/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the amount of British-grown wheat used in bio-fuel production.","true","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","194276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45806","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-02","<p> </p><p>The Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratories Agency (AHVLA) carries out non-discriminatory, risk-based inspections of animals, means of transport and accompanying documentation, as required by Council Regulation (EC) 1/2005. This Regulation is implemented in England by The Welfare of Animals (Transport) (England) Order 2006 (WATEO).</p><p>Local authorities are responsible for enforcement of this legislation, in terms of investigating and, where appropriate, taking prosecution action against any transporters alleged to have committed an offence.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45806/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45806/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-03-28","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that (a) the welfare of horses is considered a priority in live exports and (b) laws relating to the welfare of horses are being enforced.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","194277"
